# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: keel-laying
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] This was followed by the age of Classical Greece, from the Greco-Persian Wars to the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC, and which included the Golden Age of Athens and the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The unification of Greece by Macedon under Philip II and subsequent conquest of the Achaemenid Empire by Alexander the Great spread Hellenistic civilization across the Middle East.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Classical Greek culture, especially philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-greece] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In modern historiography, **ancient Rome** is the Roman civilisation from the founding of the Italian city of Rome in the 8th century BC to the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] It encompasses the Roman Kingdom (753–509 BC), the Roman Republic (509‍–‍27 BC), and the Roman Empire (27 BC – 476 AD) until the fall of the western empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome began as an Italic settlement, traditionally dated to 753 BC, beside the River Tiber in the Italian Peninsula.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The settlement grew into the city and polity of Rome, and came to control its neighbours through a combination of treaties and military strength.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] It eventually controlled the Italian Peninsula, assimilating the Greek culture of southern Italy (Magna Graecia) and the Etruscan culture, and then became the dominant power in the Mediterranean region and parts of Europe.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] At its height it controlled the North African coast, Egypt, Southern Europe, and most of Western Europe, the Balkans, Crimea, and much of the Middle East, including Anatolia, the Levant, and parts of Mesopotamia and Arabia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] That empire was among the largest empires in the ancient world, covering around 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles) in AD 117, with an estimated 50 to 90 million inhabitants, roughly 20% of the world's population at the time.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman state evolved from an elective monarchy to a classical republic and then to an increasingly autocratic military dictatorship during the Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome is often grouped into classical antiquity together with ancient Greece, and their similar cultures and societies are known as the Greco-Roman world.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Roman civilisation has contributed to modern language, religion, society, technology, law, politics, government, warfare, art, literature, architecture, and engineering.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Rome professionalised and expanded its military and created a system of government called *res publica*, the inspiration for modern republics such as the United States and France.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] It achieved impressive technological and architectural feats, such as the empire-wide construction of aqueducts and roads, as well as more grandiose monuments and facilities.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence of settlement around Rome starts to emerge c.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Large-scale organisation appears only c.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] 800 BC, with the first graves in the Esquiline Hill's necropolis, along with a clay and timber wall on the bottom of the Palatine Hill dating to the middle of the 8th century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] 650 BC, the Romans started to drain the valley between the Capitoline and Palatine Hills, where today sits the Roman Forum.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] By the 6th century BC, the Romans were constructing the Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus on the Capitoline and expanding to the Forum Boarium located between the Capitoline and Aventine Hills.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans themselves had a founding myth, attributing their city to Romulus and Remus, offspring of Mars and a princess of the mythical city of Alba Longa.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The sons, sentenced to death, were rescued by a wolf and returned to restore the Alban king and found a city.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After a dispute, Romulus killed Remus and became the city's sole founder.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The area of his initial settlement on the Palatine Hill was later known as Roma quadrata ('Square Rome').
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The story dates at least to the 3rd century BC, and the later Roman antiquarian Marcus Terentius Varro placed the city's foundation to 753 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Another legend, recorded by Greek historian Dionysius of Halicarnassus, says that Prince Aeneas led a group of Trojans on a sea voyage to found a new Troy after the Trojan War.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] They landed on the banks of the Tiber River and a woman travelling with them, Roma, torched their ships to prevent them from leaving again.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman poet Virgil recounted this legend in his classical epic poem the *Aeneid*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Literary and archaeological evidence is clear on there having been kings in Rome, attested in fragmentary 6th-century BC texts.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Long after the abolition of the Roman monarchy, a vestigial *rex sacrorum* was retained to exercise the monarch's former priestly functions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans believed that their monarchy was elective, with seven legendary kings who were largely unrelated by blood.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Evidence of Roman expansion is clear in the 6th century BC; by its end, Rome controlled a territory of some 780 square kilometres (300 square miles) with a population perhaps as high as 35,000.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] 625 BC; the Romans attributed the creation of their first popular organisations and the Senate to the regal period as well.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Rome also started to extend its control over its Latin neighbours.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] While later Roman stories like the *Aeneid* asserted that all Latins descended from the character Aeneas, a common culture is attested to archaeologically.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Attested to reciprocal rights of marriage and citizenship between Latin cities—the *Jus Latii*—along with shared religious festivals, further indicate a shared culture.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century, most of this area had become dominated by the Romans.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century BC, Rome and many of its Italian neighbours entered a period of turbulence.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence implies some degree of large-scale warfare.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] According to tradition and later writers such as Livy, the Roman Republic was established c.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] 509 BC, when the last of the seven kings of Rome, Tarquin the Proud, was deposed and a system based on annually elected magistrates and various representative assemblies was established.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] A constitution set a series of checks and balances, and a separation of powers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The most important magistrates were the two consuls, who together exercised executive authority such as *imperium*, or military command.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The consuls had to work with the Senate, which was initially an advisory council of the ranking nobility, or patricians, but grew in size and power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Other magistrates of the Republic include tribunes, quaestors, aediles, praetors and censors.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The magistracies were originally restricted to patricians, but were later opened to common people, or plebeians.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Republican voting assemblies included the *comitia centuriata* ('centuriate assembly'), which voted on matters of war and peace and elected men to the most important offices, and the *comitia tributa* ('tribal assembly'), which elected less important offices.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the 4th century BC, Rome had come under attack by the Gauls, who now extended their power in the Italian peninsula beyond the Po Valley and through Etruria.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] On 16 July 390 BC, a Gallic army under the leadership of tribal chieftain Brennus, defeated the Romans at the Battle of the Allia and marched to Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls looted and burned the city, then laid siege to the Capitoline Hill, where some Romans had barricaded themselves, for seven months.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls then agreed to give the Romans peace in exchange for 1000 pounds of gold.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] According to later legend, the Roman supervising the weighing noticed that the Gauls were using false scales.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans then took up arms and defeated the Gauls.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans gradually subdued the other peoples on the Italian peninsula, including the Etruscans.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The last threat to Roman hegemony in Italy came when Tarentum, a major Greek colony, enlisted the aid of Pyrrhus of Epirus in 281 BC, but this effort failed as well.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans secured their conquests by founding Roman colonies in strategic areas, thereby establishing stable control over the region.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the 3rd century BC Rome faced a new and formidable opponent: Carthage, the other major power in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The First Punic War began in 264 BC, when the city of Messana asked for Carthage's help in their conflicts with Hiero II of Syracuse.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After the Carthaginian intercession, Messana asked Rome to expel the Carthaginians.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Rome entered this war because Syracuse and Messana were too close to the newly conquered Greek cities of Southern Italy and Carthage was now able to make an offensive through Roman territory; along with this, Rome could extend its domain over Sicily.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage was a maritime power, and the Roman lack of ships and naval experience made the path to the victory a long and difficult one for the Roman Republic.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Despite this, after more than 20 years of war, Rome defeated Carthage and a peace treaty was signed.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Among the reasons for the Second Punic War was the subsequent war reparations Carthage acquiesced to at the end of the First Punic War.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The war began with the audacious invasion of Hispania by Hannibal, who marched through Hispania to the Italian Alps.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Hannibal's invasion lasted over 16 years, ravaging Italy, but ultimately Carthage was defeated in the decisive Battle of Zama in October 202 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] More than a half century after these events, Carthage was left humiliated and the Republic's focus was now directed towards the Hellenistic kingdoms of Greece and revolts in Hispania.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] However, Carthage, having paid the war indemnity, felt that its commitments and submission to Rome had ceased, a vision not shared by the Roman Senate.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Third Punic War began when Rome declared war against Carthage in 149 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage resisted well at the first strike but could not withstand the attack of Scipio Aemilianus, who entirely destroyed the city, enslaved all the citizens and gained control of that region, which became the province of Africa.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] All these wars resulted in Rome's first overseas conquests (Sicily, Hispania and Africa) and the rise of Rome as a significant imperial power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating the Macedonian and Seleucid Empires in the 2nd century BC, the Romans became the dominant people of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms brought the Roman and Greek cultures in closer contact and the Roman elite, once rural, became cosmopolitan.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Foreign dominance led to internal strife.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Senators became rich at the provinces' expense; soldiers, who were mostly small-scale farmers, were away from home longer and could not maintain their land; and the increased reliance on foreign slaves and the growth of *latifundia* reduced the availability of paid work.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Income from war booty, mercantilism in the new provinces, and tax farming created new economic opportunities for the wealthy, forming a new class of merchants, called the equestrians.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The **lex Claudia** forbade members of the Senate from engaging in commerce, so while the equestrians could theoretically join the Senate, they were severely restricted in political power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate squabbled perpetually, repeatedly blocked important land reforms and refused to give the equestrian class a larger say in the government.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Violent gangs of the urban unemployed, controlled by rival Senators, intimidated the electorate through violence.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The situation came to a head in the late 2nd century BC under the Gracchi brothers, a pair of tribunes who attempted to pass land reform legislation that would redistribute the major patrician landholdings among the plebeians.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Both brothers were killed and the Senate passed reforms reversing the Gracchi brother's actions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] This led to the growing divide of the plebeian groups (*populares*) and equestrian classes (*optimates*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Gaius Marius soon became a leader of the Republic, holding the first of his seven consulships (an unprecedented number) in 107 BC by arguing that his former patron Quintus Caecilius Metellus Numidicus was not able to defeat and capture the Numidian king Jugurtha.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Marius then started his military reform: in his recruitment to fight Jugurtha, he levied the very poor (an innovation), and many landless men entered the army.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Marius was elected for five consecutive consulships from 104 to 100 BC, as Rome needed a military leader to defeat the Cimbri and the Teutones, who were threatening Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After Marius's retirement, Rome had a brief peace, during which the Italian *socii* ('allies') requested Roman citizenship and voting rights.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The reformist Marcus Livius Drusus supported their legal process but was assassinated, and the *socii* revolted against the Romans in the Social War.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] At one point both consuls were killed; Marius was appointed to command the army together with Lucius Julius Caesar and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Social War, Marius and Sulla were the premier military men in Rome and their partisans were in conflict, both sides jostling for power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 88 BC, Sulla was elected for his first consulship and his first assignment was to defeat Mithridates VI of Pontus, whose intentions were to conquer the Eastern part of the Roman territories.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] However, Marius's partisans managed his installation to the military command, defying Sulla and the Senate.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] To consolidate his own power, Sulla conducted a surprising and illegal action: he marched to Rome with his legions, killing all those who showed support to Marius's cause.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the following year, 87 BC, Marius, who had fled at Sulla's march, returned to Rome while Sulla was campaigning in Greece.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He seized power along with the consul Lucius Cornelius Cinna and killed the other consul, Gnaeus Octavius, achieving his seventh consulship.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Marius and Cinna revenged their partisans by conducting a massacre.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Marius died in 86 BC, due to age and poor health, just a few months after seizing power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Cinna exercised absolute power until his death in 84 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After returning from his Eastern campaigns, Sulla had a free path to reestablish his own power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 83 BC he made his second march on Rome and began a time of terror: thousands of nobles, knights and senators were executed.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla held two dictatorships and one more consulship, which began the crisis and decline of Roman Republic.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the mid-1st century BC, Roman politics were restless.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Political divisions in Rome split into one of two groups, *populares* (who hoped for the support of the people) and *optimates* (the 'best', who wanted to maintain exclusive aristocratic control).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla overthrew all populist leaders and his constitutional reforms removed powers (such as those of the tribune of the plebs) that had supported populist approaches.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Meanwhile, social and economic stresses continued to build; Rome had become a metropolis with a super-rich aristocracy, debt-ridden aspirants, and a large proletariat often of impoverished farmers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The latter groups supported the Catilinarian conspiracy—a resounding failure since the consul Marcus Tullius Cicero quickly arrested and executed the main leaders.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Julius Caesar reconciled the two most powerful men in Rome: Marcus Licinius Crassus, who had financed much of his earlier career, and Crassus' rival, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (anglicised as Pompey), to whom he married his daughter.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He formed them into a new informal alliance including himself, the First Triumvirate ('three men').
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's daughter died in childbirth in 54 BC, and in 53 BC, Crassus invaded Parthia and was killed in the Battle of Carrhae; the Triumvirate disintegrated.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar conquered Gaul, obtained immense wealth, respect in Rome and the loyalty of battle-hardened legions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He became a threat to Pompey and was loathed by many *optimates*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Confident that Caesar could be stopped by legal means, Pompey's party tried to strip Caesar of his legions, a prelude to Caesar's trial, impoverishment, and exile.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] To avoid this fate, Caesar crossed the Rubicon River and invaded Rome in 49 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Battle of Pharsalus was a brilliant victory for Caesar and in this and other campaigns, he destroyed all of the *optimates* leaders: Metellus Scipio, Cato the Younger, and Pompey's son, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar was now pre-eminent over Rome: in five years he held four consulships, two ordinary dictatorships, and two special dictatorships, one for perpetuity.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered in 44 BC, on the Ides of March by the *Liberatores*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's assassination caused political and social turmoil in Rome; the city was ruled by his friend and colleague, Mark Antony.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Soon afterward, Octavian, whom Caesar adopted through his will, arrived in Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian (historians regard Octavius as Octavian due to the Roman naming conventions) tried to align himself with the Caesarian faction.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 43 BC, along with Antony and Marcus Aemilius Lepidus, Caesar's best friend, he legally established the Second Triumvirate.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Upon its formation, 130–300 senators were executed, and their property was confiscated, due to their supposed support for the *Liberatores*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 42 BC, the Senate deified Caesar as *Divus Iulius*; Octavian thus became *Divi filius*, the son of the deified.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the same year, Octavian and Antony defeated both Caesar's assassins and the leaders of the *Liberatores*, Marcus Junius Brutus and Gaius Cassius Longinus, in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate was marked by the proscriptions of many senators and *equites*: after a revolt led by Antony's brother Lucius Antonius, more than 300 senators and *equites* involved were executed, although Lucius was spared.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Triumvirate divided the Empire among the triumvirs: Lepidus was given charge of Africa, Antony, the eastern provinces, and Octavian remained in Italia and controlled Hispania and Gaul.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate expired in 38 BC but was renewed for five more years.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] However, the relationship between Octavian and Antony had deteriorated, and Lepidus was forced to retire in 36 BC after betraying Octavian in Sicily.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Triumvirate, Antony was living in Ptolemaic Egypt, ruled by his lover, Cleopatra VII.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Antony's affair with Cleopatra was seen as an act of treason, since she was queen of another country.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Additionally, Antony adopted a lifestyle considered too extravagant and Hellenistic for a Roman statesman.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Following Antony's Donations of Alexandria, which gave to Cleopatra the title of "Queen of Kings", and to Antony's and Cleopatra's children the regal titles to the newly conquered Eastern territories, war between Octavian and Antony broke out.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian annihilated Egyptian forces in the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Now Egypt was conquered by the Roman Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 27 BC and at the age of 36, Octavian was the sole Roman leader.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In that year, he took the name *Augustus*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] That event is usually taken by historians as the beginning of Roman Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Officially, the government was republican, but Augustus assumed absolute powers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His reform of the government brought about a two-century period colloquially referred to by Romans as the Pax Romana.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudian dynasty was established by Augustus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The emperors of this dynasty were Augustus, Tiberius, Caligula, Claudius and Nero.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians started the destruction of republican values, but on the other hand, they boosted Rome's status as the central power in the Mediterranean region.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] While Caligula and Nero are usually remembered in popular culture as dysfunctional emperors, Augustus and Claudius are remembered as successful in politics and the military.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] This dynasty instituted imperial tradition in Rome and frustrated any attempt to reestablish a Republic.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] 27 BC – AD 14) gathered almost all the republican powers under his official title, *princeps*, and diminished the political influence of the senatorial class by boosting the equestrian class.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The senators lost their right to rule certain provinces, like Egypt, since the governor of that province was directly nominated by the emperor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The creation of the Praetorian Guard and his reforms in the military, creating a standing army with a fixed size of 28 legions, ensured his total control over the army.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Compared with the Second Triumvirate's epoch, Augustus' reign as *princeps* was very peaceful, which led the people and the nobles of Rome to support Augustus, increasing his strength in political affairs.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His generals were responsible for the field command, gaining such commanders as Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa, Nero Claudius Drusus and Germanicus much respect from the populace and the legions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus intended to extend the Roman Empire to the whole known world, and in his reign, Rome conquered Cantabria, Aquitania, Raetia, Dalmatia, Illyricum and Pannonia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Under Augustus' reign, Roman literature grew steadily in what is known as the Golden Age of Latin Literature.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Poets like Virgil, Horace, Ovid and Rufus developed a rich literature, and were close friends of Augustus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Along with Maecenas, he sponsored patriotic poems, such as Virgil's epic *Aeneid* and historiographical works like those of Livy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus continued the changes to the calendar promoted by Caesar, and the month of August is named after him.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus brought a peaceful and thriving era to Rome, known as *Pax Romana*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians continued to rule Rome after Augustus' death in 14 AD and remained in power until the death of Nero in 68 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Influenced by his wife, Livia Drusilla, Augustus appointed her son from another marriage, Tiberius, as his heir.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate agreed with the succession, and granted to Tiberius the same titles and honours once granted to Augustus: the title of *princeps* and *Pater patriae*, and the Civic Crown.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] However, Tiberius was not an enthusiast for political affairs: after agreement with the Senate, he retired to Capri in 26 AD, and left control of the city of Rome in the hands of the praetorian prefect Sejanus (until 31 AD) and Macro (from 31 to 37 AD).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The male line of the Julio-Claudians was limited to Tiberius' nephew Claudius, his grandson Tiberius Gemellus and his grand-nephew Caligula.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] As Gemellus was still a child, Caligula was chosen to rule the empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He was a popular leader in the first half of his reign, but became a crude and insane tyrant in his years controlling government.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Praetorian Guard murdered Caligula four years after the death of Tiberius, and, with belated support from the senators, proclaimed his uncle Claudius as the new emperor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was not as authoritarian as Tiberius and Caligula.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius conquered Lycia and Thrace; his most important deed was the beginning of the conquest of Britannia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was poisoned by his wife, Agrippina the Younger in 54 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His heir was Nero, son of Agrippina and her former husband, since Claudius' son Britannicus had not reached manhood upon his father's death.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Nero sent his general, Suetonius Paulinus, to invade modern-day Wales, where he encountered stiff resistance.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Celts there were independent, tough, resistant to tax collectors, and fought Paulinus as he battled his way across from east to west.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] It took him a long time to reach the north-west coast, and in 60 AD he finally crossed the Menai Strait to the sacred island of Mona (Anglesey), the last stronghold of the druids.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His soldiers attacked the island and massacred the druids: men, women and children, destroyed the shrine and the sacred groves and threw many of the sacred standing stones into the sea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] While Paulinus and his troops were massacring druids in Mona, the tribes of modern-day East Anglia staged a revolt led by queen Boadicea of the Iceni.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The rebels sacked and burned Camulodunum, Londinium and Verulamium (modern-day Colchester, London and St Albans respectively) before they were crushed by Paulinus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Boadicea, like Cleopatra before her, committed suicide to avoid the disgrace of being paraded in triumph in Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Nero is widely known as the first persecutor of Christians and for the Great Fire of Rome, rumoured to have been started by the emperor himself.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] A conspiracy against Nero in 65 AD under Calpurnius Piso failed, but in 68 AD the armies under Julius Vindex in Gaul and Servius Sulpicius Galba in modern-day Spain revolted.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Deserted by the Praetorian Guards and condemned to death by the senate, Nero killed himself.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Flavians were the second dynasty to rule Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] By 68 AD, the year of Nero's death, there was no chance of a return to the Republic, and so a new emperor had to arise.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After the turmoil in the Year of the Four Emperors, Titus Flavius Vespasianus (anglicised as Vespasian) took control of the empire and established a new dynasty.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Under the Flavians, Rome continued its expansion, and the state remained secure.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The most significant military campaign undertaken during the Flavian period was the siege and destruction of Jerusalem in 70 AD by Titus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The destruction of the city was the culmination of the Roman campaign in Judea following the Jewish uprising of 66 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Temple was completely demolished, after which Titus' soldiers proclaimed him *imperator* in honour of the victory.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Jerusalem was sacked and much of the population killed or dispersed.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Josephus claims that 1,100,000 people were killed during the siege, of whom a majority were Jewish, and 97,000 were captured and enslaved.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Many fled to areas around the Mediterranean.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was a general under Claudius and Nero and fought as a commander in the First Jewish-Roman War.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Following the turmoil of the Year of the Four Emperors, in 69 AD, four emperors were enthroned in turn: Galba, Otho, Vitellius, and, lastly, Vespasian, who crushed Vitellius' forces and became emperor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He reconstructed many buildings which were uncompleted, like a statue of Apollo and the temple of *Divus Claudius* ("the deified Claudius"), both initiated by Nero.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Buildings destroyed by the Great Fire of Rome were rebuilt, and he revitalised the Capitol.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian started the construction of the Flavian Amphitheater, commonly known as the Colosseum.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The historians Josephus and Pliny the Elder wrote their works during Vespasian's reign.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was Josephus' sponsor and Pliny dedicated his *Naturalis Historia* to Titus, son of Vespasian.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian sent legions to defend the eastern frontier in Cappadocia, extended the occupation in Britannia (modern-day England, Wales and southern Scotland) and reformed the tax system.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He finished the Flavian Amphitheater, using war spoils from the First Jewish-Roman War, and hosted victory games that lasted for a hundred days.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] These games included gladiatorial combats, horse races and a sensational mock naval battle on the flooded grounds of the Colosseum.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Titus died of fever in 81 AD, and was succeeded by his brother Domitian.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] As emperor, Domitian showed the characteristics of a tyrant.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He ruled for fifteen years, during which time he acquired a reputation for self-promotion as a living god.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed at least two temples in honour of Jupiter, the supreme deity in Roman religion.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered following a plot within his own household.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Following Domitian's murder, the Senate rapidly appointed Nerva as Emperor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva had noble ancestry, and he had served as an advisor to Nero and the Flavians.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His rule restored many of the traditional liberties of Rome's upper classes, which Domitian had over-ridden.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva–Antonine dynasty from 96 AD to 192 AD included the "five good emperors" Nerva, Trajan, Hadrian, Antoninus Pius and Marcus Aurelius.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva-Antonine dynasty came to an end with Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva abdicated and died in 98 AD, and was succeeded by the general Trajan.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan is credited with the restoration of traditional privileges and rights of commoner and senatorial classes, which later Roman historians claim to have been eroded during Domitian's autocracy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan fought three Dacian wars, winning territories roughly equivalent to modern-day Romania and Moldova.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He undertook an ambitious public building program in Rome, including Trajan's Forum, Trajan's Market and Trajan's Column, with the architect Apollodorus of Damascus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He remodelled the Pantheon and extended the Circus Maximus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia appointed a king for Armenia without consulting Rome, Trajan declared war on Parthia and deposed the king of Armenia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 115 he took the Northern Mesopotamian cities of Nisibis and Batnae, organised a province of Mesopotamia (116), and issued coins that claimed Armenia and Mesopotamia were under the authority of the Roman people.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year, he captured Seleucia and the Parthian capital Ctesiphon (near modern Baghdad).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating a Parthian revolt and a Jewish revolt, he withdrew due to health issues, and in 117, he died of edema.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Under Trajan, the Roman Empire had reached the peak of its territorial expansion.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Rome's dominion now spanned 5.0 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan's successor Hadrian withdrew all the troops stationed in Parthia, Armenia and Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq), abandoning Trajan's conquests.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian's army crushed a revolt in Mauretania and the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] This was the last large-scale Jewish revolt against the Romans, and was suppressed with massive repercussions in Judea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Jews were killed.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian renamed the province of Judea "Provincia Syria Palaestina", after one of Judea's most hated enemies.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed fortifications and walls, like the celebrated Hadrian's Wall which separated Roman Britannia and the tribes of modern-day Scotland.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian promoted culture, especially the Greek.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He forbade torture and humanised the laws.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His many building projects included aqueducts, baths, libraries and theatres; additionally, he travelled nearly every province in the Empire to review military and infrastructural conditions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Following Hadrian's death in 138 AD, his successor Antoninus Pius built temples, theatres, and mausoleums, promoted the arts and sciences, and bestowed honours and financial rewards upon the teachers of rhetoric and philosophy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] On becoming emperor, Antoninus made few initial changes, leaving intact as far as possible the arrangements instituted by his predecessor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Antoninus expanded Roman Britannia by invading what is now southern Scotland and building the Antonine Wall.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He also continued Hadrian's policy of humanising the laws.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His reign was the most peaceful in the entire history of Roman Empire, he left "an empire in very fine shape.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] It was a height that, arguably, it would never reach again." He died in 161 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Marcus Aurelius, known as the Philosopher, was the last of the Five Good Emperors.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He was a stoic philosopher and wrote the *Meditations*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He defeated barbarian tribes in the Marcomannic Wars as well as the Parthian Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His co-emperor, Lucius Verus, died in 169 AD, probably from the Antonine Plague, a pandemic that killed nearly five million people through the Empire in 165–180 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] From Nerva to Marcus Aurelius, the empire achieved an unprecedented status.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The powerful influence of laws and manners had gradually cemented the union of the provinces.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] All the citizens enjoyed and abused the advantages of wealth.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The image of a free constitution was preserved with decent reverence.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman senate appeared to possess the sovereign authority, and devolved on the emperors all the executive powers of government.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Gibbon declared the rule of these "Five Good Emperors" the golden era of the Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] During this time, Rome reached its greatest territorial extent.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius, became emperor after his father's death.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He is not counted as one of the Five Good Emperors, due to his direct kinship with the latter emperor; in addition, he was militarily passive.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus was killed by a conspiracy involving Quintus Aemilius Laetus and his wife Marcia in late 192 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The following year is known as the Year of the Five Emperors, during which Helvius Pertinax, Didius Julianus, Pescennius Niger, Clodius Albinus and Septimius Severus held the imperial dignity.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Pertinax, a member of the senate who had been one of Marcus Aurelius's right-hand men, was the choice of Laetus, and he ruled vigorously and judiciously.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Laetus soon became jealous and instigated Pertinax's murder by the Praetorian Guard, who then auctioned the empire to the highest bidder, Didius Julianus, for 25,000 sesterces per man.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The people of Rome were appalled and appealed to the frontier legions to save them.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The legions of three frontier provinces—Britannia, Pannonia Superior, and Syria—resented being excluded from the "donative" and replied by declaring their individual generals to be emperor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Lucius Septimius Severus Geta, the Pannonian commander, bribed the opposing forces, pardoned the Praetorian Guards and installed himself as emperor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He and his successors governed with the legions' support.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The changes on coinage and military expenditures were the root of the financial crisis that marked the Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Severus was enthroned after invading Rome and having Didius Julianus killed.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Severus attempted to revive totalitarianism and, addressing the Roman people and Senate, praised the severity and cruelty of Marius and Sulla, which worried the senators.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia invaded Roman territory, Severus successfully waged war against that country.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Notwithstanding this military success, Severus failed in invading Hatra, a rich Arabian city.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Severus killed his legate, who was gaining respect from the legions; and his soldiers fell victim to famine.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After this disastrous campaign, he withdrew.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Severus also intended to vanquish the whole of Britannia.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] To achieve this, he waged war against the Caledonians.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] However, he became ill and died in 211 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His sons Caracalla and Geta were made emperors.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Caracalla had his brother, a youth, assassinated in his mother's arms, and may have murdered 20,000 of Geta's followers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He continued Severus' policy and gained respect from the legions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Knowing that the citizens of Alexandria disliked him and were denigrating his character, Caracalla served a banquet for its notable citizens, after which his soldiers killed all the guests.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] From the security of the temple of Sarapis, he then directed an indiscriminate slaughter of Alexandria's people.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 212, he issued the Edict of Caracalla, giving full Roman citizenship to all free men living in the Empire, with the exception of the *dediticii*, people who had become subject to Rome through surrender in war, and freed slaves.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Mary Beard points to the edict as a fundamental turning point, after which *Rome* was "effectively a new state masquerading under an old name".
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus conspired to have Caracalla assassinated by one of his soldiers during a pilgrimage to the Temple of the Moon in Carrhae, in 217 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus assumed power, but soon removed himself from Rome to the east and Antioch.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His brief reign ended in 218, when the youngster Bassianus, high priest of the temple of the Sun at Emesa, and supposedly illegitimate son of Caracalla, was declared Emperor by the disaffected soldiers of Macrinus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted the name of Antoninus but history has named him after his Sun god Elagabalus, represented on Earth in the form of a large black stone.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] An incompetent and lascivious ruler, Elagabalus adopted his cousin Severus Alexander, as Caesar, but subsequently grew jealous and attempted to assassinate him.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] However, the Praetorian guard preferred Alexander, murdered Elagabalus, dragged his mutilated corpse through the streets of Rome, and threw it into the Tiber.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Alexander waged war against many foes, including the revitalised Persia and also the Germanic peoples, who invaded Gaul.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His losses generated dissatisfaction among his soldiers, and some of them murdered him during his Germanic campaign in 235 AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] A disastrous scenario emerged after the death of Alexander Severus: the Roman state was plagued by civil wars, external invasions, political chaos, pandemics and economic depression.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The old Roman values had fallen, and Mithraism and Christianity had begun to spread through the populace.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Emperors were no longer men linked with nobility; they usually were born in lower-classes of distant parts of the Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] These men rose to prominence through military ranks, and became emperors through civil wars.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] There were 26 emperors in a 49-year period, a signal of political instability.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Maximinus Thrax was the first ruler of that time, governing for just three years.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Others ruled just for a few months, like Gordian I, Gordian II, Balbinus and Hostilian.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The population and the frontiers were abandoned, since the emperors were mostly concerned with defeating rivals and establishing their power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The economy also suffered: massive military expenditures from the Severi caused a devaluation of Roman coins.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Hyperinflation came at this time as well.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Plague of Cyprian broke out in 250 and killed a huge portion of the population.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 260 AD, the provinces of Syria Palaestina, Asia Minor and Egypt separated from the rest of the Roman state to form the Palmyrene Empire, ruled by Queen Zenobia and centered on Palmyra.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year the Gallic Empire was created by Postumus, retaining Britannia and Gaul.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] These countries separated from Rome after the capture of emperor Valerian by the Sassanids of Persia, the first Roman ruler to be captured by his enemies; it was a humiliating fact for the Romans.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis began to recede during the reigns of Claudius Gothicus (268–270), who defeated the Gothic invaders, and Aurelian (271–275), who reconquered both the Gallic and Palmyrene Empires.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis was overcome during the reign of Diocletian.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 284 AD, Diocletian was hailed as Imperator by the eastern army.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian healed the empire from the crisis, by political and economic shifts.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] A new form of government was established: the Tetrarchy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Empire was divided among four emperors, two in the West and two in the East.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The first tetrarchs were Diocletian (in the East), Maximian (in the West), and two junior emperors, Galerius (in the East) and Flavius Constantius (in the West).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] To adjust the economy, Diocletian made several tax reforms.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian expelled the Persians who plundered Syria and conquered some barbarian tribes with Maximian.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted many behaviours of Eastern monarchs.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Anyone in the presence of the emperor had now to prostrate himself—a common act in the East, but never practised in Rome before.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian did not use a disguised form of Republic, as the other emperors since Augustus had done.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Between 290 and 330, half a dozen new capitals had been established by the members of the Tetrarchy, officially or not: Antioch, Nicomedia, Thessalonike, Sirmium, Milan, and Trier.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian was also responsible for a significant Christian persecution.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 303 he and Galerius started the persecution and ordered the destruction of all the Christian churches and scripts and forbade Christian worship.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian abdicated in 305 AD together with Maximian, thus, he was the first Roman emperor to resign.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] His reign ended the traditional form of imperial rule, the Principate (from princeps) and started the Tetrarchy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine assumed the empire as a tetrarch in 306.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He conducted many wars against the other tetrarchs.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 313, he issued the Edict of Milan, which granted liberty for Christians to profess their religion.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine was converted to Christianity, enforcing the Christian faith.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He began the Christianization of the Empire and of Europe—a process concluded by the Catholic Church in the Middle Ages.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] He was defeated by the Franks and the Alamanni during 306–308.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 324 he defeated another tetrarch, Licinius, and controlled all the empire, as it was before Diocletian.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] To celebrate his victories and Christianity's relevance, he rebuilt Byzantium and renamed it Nova Roma ("New Rome"); but the city soon gained the informal name of Constantinople ("City of Constantine").
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The reign of Julian, who under the influence of his adviser Mardonius attempted to restore Classical Roman and Hellenistic religion, only briefly interrupted the succession of Christian emperors.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Constantinople served as a new capital for the Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In fact, Rome had lost its central importance since the Crisis of the Third Century—Mediolanum was the western capital from 286 to 330, until the reign of Honorius, when Ravenna was made capital, in the 5th century.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine's administrative and monetary reforms, that reunited the Empire under one emperor, and rebuilt the city of Byzantium, as Constantinopolis Nova Roma, changed the high period of the ancient world.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the late 4th and 5th centuries the Western Empire entered a critical stage which terminated with the fall of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The next emperor, Theodosius I (379–395), gave even more force to the Christian faith, and after his death, the Empire was divided into the Eastern Roman Empire, ruled by Arcadius and the Western Roman Empire, commanded by Honorius, both of which were Theodosius' sons.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The situation became more critical in 408, after the death of Stilicho, a general who tried to reunite the Empire and repel barbarian invasion in the early years of the 5th century.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 410, the Theodosian dynasty saw the Visigoths sack Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] During the 5th century, the Western Empire experienced a significant reduction of its territory.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Vandals conquered North Africa, the Visigoths claimed the southern part of Gaul, Gallaecia was taken by the Suebi, Britannia was abandoned by the central government, and the Empire suffered further from the invasions of Attila, chief of the Huns.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] General Orestes refused to meet the demands of the barbarian "allies" who now formed the army, and tried to expel them from Italy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Unhappy with this, their chieftain Odoacer defeated and killed Orestes, invaded Ravenna and dethroned Romulus Augustus, son of Orestes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] This event of 476, usually marks the end of Classical antiquity and beginning of the Middle Ages.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman noble and former emperor Julius Nepos continued to rule as emperor from Dalmatia even after the deposition of Romulus Augustus until his death in 480.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Some historians consider him to be the last emperor of the Western Empire instead of Romulus Augustus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After 1200 years of independence and nearly 700 years as a great power, the rule of Rome in the West ended.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Various reasons for Rome's fall have been proposed, including loss of Republicanism, moral decay, military tyranny, class war, slavery, economic stagnation, environmental change, disease, the decline of the Roman race, as well as the inevitable ebb and flow that all civilisations experience.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Empire survived for almost 1000 years after the fall of its Western counterpart and became the most stable Christian realm during the Middle Ages.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] During the 6th century, Justinian reconquered the Italian peninsula from the Ostrogoths, North Africa from the Vandals, and southern Hispania from the Visigoths.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] But within a few years of Justinian's death, Byzantine possessions in Italy were greatly reduced by the Lombards who settled in the peninsula.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the east, partially due to the weakening effect of the Plague of Justinian as well as a series of mutually destructive wars against the Persian Sassanian Empire, the Byzantines were threatened by the rise of Islam.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Its followers rapidly brought about the conquest of the Levant, the conquest of North Africa and the conquest of Egypt during the Arab–Byzantine wars, and soon presented a direct threat to Constantinople.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the following century, the Arabs captured southern Italy and Sicily.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In the west, Slavic populations penetrated deep into the Balkans.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Byzantine Romans, however, managed to stop further Islamic expansion into their lands during the 8th century and, beginning in the 9th century, reclaimed parts of the conquered lands.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] In 1000 AD, the Eastern Empire was at its height: Basil II reconquered Bulgaria and Armenia, and culture and trade flourished.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] However, soon after, this expansion was abruptly stopped in 1071 with the Byzantine defeat in the Battle of Manzikert.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The aftermath of this battle sent the empire into a protracted period of decline.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] Two decades of internal strife and Turkic invasions ultimately led Emperor Alexios I Komnenos to send a call for help to the Western European kingdoms in 1095.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The West responded with the Crusades, eventually resulting in the Sack of Constantinople by participants of the Fourth Crusade.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of Constantinople in 1204 fragmented what remained of the Empire into successor states; the ultimate victor was the Empire of Nicaea.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] After the recapture of Constantinople by Imperial forces, the Empire was little more than a Greek state confined to the Aegean coast.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire collapsed when Mehmed the Conqueror conquered Constantinople on 29 May 1453.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The imperial city of Rome was the largest urban center in the empire, with a population variously estimated from 450,000 to close to one million.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Around 20% of the population under jurisdiction of ancient Rome (25–40%, depending on the standards used, in Roman Italy) lived in innumerable urban centers, with population of 10,000 and more and several military settlements, a very high rate of urbanisation by pre-industrial standards.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Most of those centers had a forum, temples, and other buildings similar to Rome's.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The average life expectancy in the Middle Empire was about 26–28 years.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The roots of the legal principles and practices of the ancient Romans may be traced to the Law of the Twelve Tables promulgated in 449 BC and to the codification of law issued by order of Emperor Justinian I around 530 AD (see *Corpus Juris Civilis*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law as preserved in Justinian's codes continued into the Byzantine Roman Empire, and formed the basis of similar codifications in continental Western Europe.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law continued, in a broader sense, to be applied throughout most of Europe until the end of the 17th century.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The major divisions of the law of ancient Rome, as contained within the Justinian and Theodosian law codes, consisted of *Jus civile*, *Jus gentium*, and *Jus naturale*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus civile* ('citizen law') was the body of common laws that applied to Roman citizens.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Urbanus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus gentium* ('law of nations') was the body of common laws that applied to foreigners, and their dealings with Roman citizens.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Peregrinus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens and foreigners.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] *Jus naturale* encompassed natural law, the body of laws that were considered common to all beings.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society is largely viewed as hierarchical, with slaves (*servi*) at the bottom, freedmen (*liberti*) above them, and free-born citizens (*cives*) at the top.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The broadest, and earliest, division was between the patricians, who could trace their ancestry to one of the 100 patriarchs at the founding of the city, and the plebeians, who could not.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] This became less important in the later Republic, as some plebeian families became wealthy and entered politics, and some patrician families fell economically.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Anyone, patrician or plebeian, who could count a consul as his ancestor was a noble (*nobilis*); a man who was the first of his family to hold the consulship, such as Marius or Cicero, was known as a *novus homo* ('new man') and ennobled his descendants.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Patrician ancestry, however, still conferred considerable prestige, and many religious offices remained restricted to patricians.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] A class division originally based on military service became more important.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Membership of these classes was determined periodically by the censors, according to property.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The wealthiest were the Senatorial class, who dominated politics and command of the army.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Next came the equestrians (*equites*, sometimes translated "knights"), originally those who could afford a warhorse, and who formed a powerful mercantile class.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Several further classes, originally based on the military equipment their members could afford, followed, with the *proletarii*, citizens who had no property other than their children, at the bottom.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Before the reforms of Marius they were ineligible for military service and are often described as being just above freed slaves in wealth and prestige.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Voting power in the Republic depended on class.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Citizens were enrolled in voting "tribes", but the tribes of the richer classes had fewer members than the poorer ones, all the *proletarii* being enrolled in a single tribe.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Voting was done in class order, from top down, and stopped as soon as most of the tribes had been reached, so the poorer classes were often unable to cast their votes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Women in ancient Rome shared some basic rights with their male counterparts, but were not fully regarded as citizens and were thus not allowed to vote or take part in politics.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] At the same time the limited rights of women were gradually expanded (due to emancipation) and women reached freedom from *pater familias*, gained property rights and even had more juridical rights than their husbands, but still no voting rights, and were absent from politics.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Allied foreign cities were often given the Latin Rights, an intermediary level between full citizens and foreigners (*peregrini*), which gave their citizens rights under Roman law and allowed their leading magistrates to become full Roman citizens.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] While there were varying degrees of Latin rights, the main division was between those *cum suffragio* ('with vote'; enrolled in a Roman tribe and able to take part in the *comitia tributa*) and *sine suffragio* ('without vote'; could not take part in Roman politics).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, there were no public schools, so boys were taught to read and write by their parents, or by educated slaves, called *paedagogi*, usually of Greek origin.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The primary aim of education during this period was to train young men in agriculture, warfare, Roman traditions, and public affairs.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Young boys learned much about civic life by accompanying their fathers to religious and political functions, including the Senate for the sons of nobles.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The sons of nobles were apprenticed to a prominent political figure at the age of 16, and campaigned with the army from the age of 17.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Educational practices were modified after the conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms in the 3rd century BC and the resulting Greek influence, although Roman educational practices were still much different from Greek ones.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning at age 12, students went to secondary schools, where the teacher (now called a *grammaticus*) taught them about Greek and Roman literature.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] At the age of 16, some students went on to rhetoric school (where the teacher, usually Greek, was called a *rhetor*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Education at this level prepared students for legal careers, and required that the students memorise the laws of Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Initially, Rome was ruled by kings, who were elected from each of Rome's major tribes in turn.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The exact nature of the king's power is uncertain.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] He may have held near-absolute power, or may have merely been the chief executive of the Senate and the people.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In military matters, the king's authority (*Imperium*) was likely absolute.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] He was also the head of the state religion.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The class struggles of the Roman Republic resulted in an unusual mixture of democracy and oligarchy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The word republic comes from the Latin *res publica*, which literally translates to 'public business'.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman laws traditionally could only be passed by a vote of the Popular assembly (Comitia Tributa).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Likewise, candidates for public positions had to run for election by the people.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] However, the Roman Senate represented an oligarchic institution, which acted as an advisory body.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the Republic, the Senate held actual authority (*auctoritas*), but no real legislative power; it was technically only an advisory council.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] However, as the Senators were individually very influential, it was difficult to accomplish anything against the collective will of the Senate.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] New senators were chosen from among the most accomplished patricians by censors (*Censura*), who could also remove a senator from his office if he was found "morally corrupt".
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Later, under the reforms of the dictator Sulla, quaestors were made automatic members of the Senate, though most of his reforms did not survive.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Republic had no fixed bureaucracy, and collected taxes through the practice of tax farming.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Government positions such as quaestor, aedile, or praefect were funded by the office-holder.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] To prevent any citizen from gaining too much power, new magistrates were elected annually and had to share power with a colleague.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] For example, under normal conditions, the highest authority was held by two consuls.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In an emergency, a temporary dictator could be appointed.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the Republic, the administrative system was revised several times to comply with new demands.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the end, it proved inefficient for controlling the ever-expanding dominion of Rome, contributing to the establishment of the Roman Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Empire, the pretense of a republican form of government was maintained.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman emperor was portrayed as only a *princeps*, or 'first citizen', and the Senate gained legislative power and all legal authority previously held by the popular assemblies.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] However, the rule of the Emperors became increasingly autocratic, and the Senate was reduced to an advisory body appointed by the Emperor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire did not inherit a set bureaucracy from the Republic, since the Republic did not have any permanent governmental structures apart from the Senate.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor appointed assistants and advisers, but the state lacked many institutions, such as a centrally planned budget.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have cited this as a significant reason for the decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] 500 BC) was, like those of other contemporary city-states influenced by Greek civilisation, a citizen *militia* that practised hoplite tactics.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] It was small and organised in five classes (in parallel to the *comitia centuriata*, the body of citizens organised politically), with three providing hoplites and two providing light infantry.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The early Roman army was tactically limited and its stance during this period was essentially defensive.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] By the 3rd century BC, the Romans abandoned the hoplite formation in favour of a more flexible system in which smaller groups of 120 (or sometimes 60) men called '*maniples* could manoeuvre more independently on the battlefield.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Thirty maniples arranged in three lines with supporting troops constituted a legion, totalling between 4,000 and 5,000 men.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The early Republican legion consisted of five sections: manipular heavy infantry (*hastati*, *principes* and *triarii*), a force of light infantry (*velites*), and the cavalry (*equites*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] With the new organisation came a new orientation toward the offensive and a much more aggressive posture toward adjoining city-states.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Until the late Republican period, the typical legionary was a property-owning citizen farmer from a rural area (an *adsiduus*) who served for particular (often annual) campaigns, and who supplied his own equipment.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] After 200 BC, economic conditions in rural areas deteriorated as manpower needs increased, so that the property qualifications for compulsory service were gradually reduced.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning in the 3rd century BC, legionaries were paid a stipend.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] By the time of Augustus, the ideal of the citizen-soldier had been abandoned and the legions had become fully professional.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] At the end of the Civil War, Augustus reorganised Roman military forces, discharging soldiers and disbanding legions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] He retained 28 legions, distributed through the provinces of the Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During the Principate, the tactical organisation of the Army continued to evolve.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The *auxilia* remained independent cohorts, and legionary troops often operated as groups of cohorts rather than as full legions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] A new and versatile type of unit, the *cohortes equitatae*, combined cavalry and legionaries in a single formation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] They could be stationed at garrisons or outposts and could fight on their own as balanced small forces or combine with similar units as a larger, legion-sized force.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] This increase in organizational flexibility helped ensure the long-term success of Roman military forces.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor Gallienus (253–268 AD) began a reorganisation that created the last military structure of the late Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Withdrawing some legionaries from the fixed bases on the border, Gallienus created mobile forces (the *comitatenses*, or field armies) and stationed them behind and at some distance from the borders as a strategic reserve.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The border troops (*limitanei*) stationed at fixed bases continued to be the first line of defence.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of the field army were regimental; *legiones* or *auxilia* for infantry and *vexillationes* for cavalry.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Nominal strengths may have been 1,200 men for infantry regiments and 600 for cavalry, but actual troop levels could have been much lower—800 infantry and 400 cavalry.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Many infantry and cavalry regiments operated in pairs under the command of a *comes*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Field armies included regiments recruited from allied tribes and known as *foederati*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] By 400 AD, *foederati* regiments had become permanently established units of the Roman army, paid and equipped by the Empire, led by a Roman tribune and used just as Roman units were used.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire also used groups of barbarians to fight along with the legions as allies without integration into the field armies, under overall command of a Roman general, but led by their own officers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Military leadership evolved over the course of the history of Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Under the monarchy, the hoplite armies were led by the kings.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During the early and middle Roman Republic, military forces were under the command of one of the two elected consuls for the year.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During the later Republic, members of the Roman Senatorial elite, as part of the normal sequence of elected public offices known as the *cursus honorum*, would have served first as *quaestor* (often posted as deputies to field commanders), then as *praetor*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Following the end of a term as praetor or consul, a Senator might be appointed by the Senate as a *propraetor* or *proconsul* (depending on the highest office held before) to govern a foreign province.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Under Augustus, whose most important political priority was to place the military under a permanent and unitary command, the Emperor was the legal commander of each legion but exercised that command through a *legatus* (legate) he appointed from the Senatorial elite.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During the later stages of the Imperial period (beginning perhaps with Diocletian), the Augustan model was abandoned.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Provincial governors were stripped of military authority, and command of the armies in a group of provinces was given to generals (*duces*) appointed by the Emperor.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] These were no longer members of the Roman elite but men who came up through the ranks and had seen much practical soldiering.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] With increasing frequency, these men attempted (sometimes successfully) to usurp the positions of the Emperors.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Decreased resources, increasing political chaos and civil war eventually left the Western Empire vulnerable to attack and takeover by neighbouring barbarian peoples.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Less is known about the Roman navy than the Roman army.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Prior to the middle of the 3rd century BC, officials known as *duumviri navales* commanded a fleet of twenty ships used mainly to control piracy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] This fleet was given up in 278 AD and replaced by allied forces.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The First Punic War required that Rome build large fleets, and it did so largely with the assistance of and financing from allies.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] This reliance on allies continued to the end of the Roman Republic.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The quinquereme was the main warship on both sides of the Punic Wars and remained the mainstay of Roman naval forces until replaced by the time of Caesar Augustus by lighter and more manoeuvrable vessels.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Ships were commanded by a *navarch*, a rank equal to a centurion, who was usually not a citizen.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Potter suggests that because the fleet was dominated by non-Romans, the navy was considered non-Roman and allowed to atrophy in times of peace.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Information suggests that by the time of the late Empire (350 AD), the Roman navy comprised several fleets including warships and merchant vessels for transportation and supply.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Warships were oared sailing galleys with three to five banks of oarsmen.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Fleet bases included such ports as Ravenna, Arles, Aquilea, Misenum and the mouth of the Somme River in the West and Alexandria and Rhodes in the East.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Flotillas of small river craft (*classes*) were part of the *limitanei* (border troops) during this period, based at fortified river harbours along the Rhine and the Danube.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] That prominent generals commanded both armies and fleets suggests that naval forces were treated as auxiliaries to the army and not as an independent service.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The details of command structure and fleet strengths during this period are not well known, although fleets were commanded by prefects.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome commanded a vast area of land, with tremendous natural and human resources.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] As such, Rome's economy remained focused on farming and trade.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Agricultural free trade changed the Italian landscape, and by the 1st century BC, vast grape and olive estates had supplanted the yeoman farmers, who were unable to match the imported grain price.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The annexation of Egypt, Sicily and Tunisia in North Africa provided a continuous supply of grains.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In turn, olive oil and wine were Italy's main exports.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Two-tier crop rotation was practised, but farm productivity was low.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Industrial and manufacturing activities were small.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The largest such activities were the mining and quarrying of stones, which provided basic construction materials for the buildings of that period.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In manufacturing, production was on a relatively small scale, and generally consisted of workshops and small factories that employed at most dozens of workers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] However, some brick factories employed hundreds of workers.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The economy of the early Republic was largely based on smallholding and paid labour.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] However, foreign wars and conquests made slaves increasingly cheap and plentiful, and by the late Republic, the economy was largely dependent on slave labour for both skilled and unskilled work.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Slaves are estimated to have constituted around 20% of the Roman Empire's population at this time and 40% in the city of Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Only in the Roman Empire, when the conquests stopped and the prices of slaves increased, did hired labour become more economical than slave ownership.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Although barter was used in ancient Rome, and often used in tax collection, Rome had a very developed coinage system, with brass, bronze, and precious metal coins in circulation throughout the Empire and beyond—some have even been discovered in India.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Before the 3rd century BC, copper was traded by weight, measured in unmarked lumps, across central Italy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The original copper coins (*as*) had a face value of one Roman pound of copper, but weighed less.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, Roman money's utility as a unit of exchange consistently exceeded its intrinsic value as metal.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] After Nero began debasing the silver denarius, its legal value was an estimated one-third greater than its intrinsic value.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Horses were expensive and other pack animals were slower.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Mass trade on the Roman roads connected military posts, where Roman markets were centered.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] As a result, there was transport of commodities between Roman regions, but increased with the rise of Roman maritime trade in the 2nd century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During that period, a trading vessel took less than a month to complete a trip from Gades to Alexandria via Ostia, spanning the entire length of the Mediterranean.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Transport by sea was around 60 times cheaper than by land, so the volume for such trips was much larger.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Some economists consider the Roman Empire a market economy, similar in its degree of capitalistic practices to the 17th-century Netherlands and 18th-century England.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of Roman society were households and families.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Groups of households connected through the male line formed a family (*gens*), based on blood ties, a common ancestry or adoption.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During the Republic, some powerful families, or *Gentes Maiores*, came to dominate political life.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Families were headed by their oldest male citizen, the *pater familias* (father of the family), who held lawful authority (*patria potestas*, 'father's power') over wives, sons, daughters, and slaves of the household, and the family's wealth.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The extreme expressions of this power—the selling or killing of family members for moral or civil offences, including simple disobedience—were very rarely exercised, and were forbidden in the Imperial era.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] A *pater familias* had moral and legal duties towards all family members.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Even the most despotic *pater familias* was expected to consult senior members of his household and *gens* over matters that affected the family's well-being and reputation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, such matters were regarded as outside the purview of the state and its magistrates; under the emperors, they were increasingly subject to state interference and legislation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Once accepted into their birth family by their fathers, children were potential heirs.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] They could not be lawfully given away, or sold into slavery.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] If parents were unable to care for their child, or if its paternity was in doubt, they could resort to infant exposure (Boswell translates this as being "offered" up to care by the gods or strangers).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] If a deformed or sickly newborn was patently "unfit to live", killing it was a duty of the *pater familias*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] A citizen father who exposed a healthy freeborn child was not punished, but automatically lost his *potestas* over that child.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Abandoned children were sometimes adopted; some would have been sold into slavery.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Slavery was near-ubiquitous and almost universally accepted.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, citizens in debt were allowed to sell their labour, and perhaps their sons, to their debtor in a limited form of slavery called *nexum* but this was abolished in the middle Republic.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Freedom was considered a natural and proper state for citizens; slaves could be lawfully freed, with consent and support of their owners, and still serve their owners' family and financial interests, as freedmen or freed women.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] This was the basis of the client-patron relationship, one of the most important features of Rome's economy and society.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In law, a *pater familias* held *potestas* over his adult sons with their own households.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] This could give rise to legal anomalies, such as adult sons also having the status of minors.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] No man could be considered a *pater familias*, nor could he truly hold property under law, while his own father lived.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During Rome's early history, married daughters came under the control (*manus*) of their husbands' *pater familias*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] By the late Republic, most married women retained lawful connection to their birth family, though any children from the marriage belonged to her husband's family.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The mother or an elderly relative often raised both boys and girls.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman moralists held that marriage and child-raising fulfilled a basic duty to family, *gens*, and the state.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Fathers usually began seeking husbands for their daughters when these reached an age between twelve and fourteen, but most commoner-class women stayed single until their twenties, and in general seem to have been far more independent than wives of the elite.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Divorce required the consent of one party, along with the return of any dowry.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Both parents had power over their children during their minority and adulthood, but husbands had much less control over their wives.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman citizen women held a restricted form of citizenship; they could not vote but were protected by law.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] They ran families, could own and run businesses, own and cultivate land, write their own wills, and plead in court on their own behalf, or on behalf of others, all under dispensation of the courts and the nominal supervision of a senior male relative.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The latter was much resented, and the former had seemingly negligible results.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Aristocratic women seem to have been increasingly disinclined to childbearing.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman hours were counted ordinally from dawn to dawn.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, if sunrise was at 6 am, then 6 to 7 am was called the 'first hour'.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Midday was called *meridies*, and it is from this word that the terms *am* (*ante meridiem*) and *pm* (*post meridiem*) stem.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The English word "noon" comes from *nona* ('ninth (hour)'), which referred to 3 pm in ancient Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had clocks (*horologia*), which included giant public sundials (*solaria*) and water clocks (*clepsydrae*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman week originally had eight days, which were identified by letters A to H, with the eighth day being the *nundinum*, or market day, a kind of weekend when farmers sold their produce on the streets.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The seven-day week, introduced from the East during the early Empire, was officially adopted during the reign of Constantine.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Romans named week days after celestial bodies from at least the 1st century AD.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman year originally had ten months from Martius (March) to December, with the winter period not included in the calendar.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The first four months were named after gods (Martius, Aprilis, Maius, Junius) and the others were numbered (Quintilis, Sextilis, September, October, November, and December).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Numa Pompilius, the second king of Rome (716–673 BC), is said to have introduced the months of January and February, both also named after gods, beginning the 12-month calendar still in use today.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In 44 BC, the month Quintilis was renamed to Julius (July) after Julius Caesar and in 8 BC, Sextilis was renamed to Augustus (August) after Augustus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had several ways of tracking years.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] One widespread way was the consular dating, which identified years by the two consuls who ruled each year.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, introduced in the late 3rd century AD, was counting years from the *indictio*, a 15-year period based on the announcement of the delivery of food and other goods to the government.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, less popular but more similar to present day, was *ab urbe condita*, which counted years from the mythical foundation of Rome in 753 BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Life in ancient Rome revolved around the city of Rome, located on seven hills.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The city had a vast number of monumental structures like the Colosseum, the Trajan's Forum and the Pantheon.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] It had theatres, gymnasiums, marketplaces, functional sewers, bath complexes complete with libraries and shops, and fountains with fresh drinking water supplied by hundreds of miles of aqueducts.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the territory under the control of ancient Rome, residential architecture ranged from modest houses to country villas.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, there were imperial residences on Palatine Hill.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The low plebeian and middle equestrian classes lived in the city center, packed into apartments, or insulae, which were almost like modern ghettos.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] These areas, often built by upper class property owners to rent, were often centred upon collegia or taberna.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] These people, provided with a free supply of grain, and entertained by gladiatorial games, were enrolled as clients of patrons among the upper class patricians, whose assistance they sought and whose interests they upheld.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The native language of the Romans was Latin, an Italic language the grammar of which relies little on word order, conveying meaning through a system of affixes attached to word stems.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Its alphabet was based on the Etruscan alphabet, which was in turn based on the Greek alphabet.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Speakers of Latin could understand both until the 7th century when spoken Latin began to diverge so much that 'Classical' or 'Good Latin' had to be learned as a second language.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] While Latin remained the main written language of the Roman Empire, Greek came to be the language spoken by the well-educated elite, as most of the literature studied by Romans was written in Greek.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Most of the emperors were bilingual but had a preference for Latin in the public sphere for political reasons, a practice that first started during the Punic wars.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the eastern part of the Roman Empire (and later the Eastern Roman Empire), Latin was never able to replace Greek, a legacy of the Hellenistic period.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Justinian would be the last emperor to use Latin in government and marks when Greek officially took over.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The expansion of the Roman Empire spread Latin throughout Europe, and Vulgar Latin evolved into many distinct Romance languages.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Archaic Roman religion, at least concerning the gods, was made up not of written narratives, but rather of complex interrelations between gods and humans.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Unlike in Greek mythology, the gods were not personified, but were vaguely defined sacred spirits called *numina*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Romans also believed that every person, place or thing had its own *genius*, or divine soul.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During the Roman Republic, Roman religion was organised under a strict system of priestly offices, which were held by men of senatorial rank.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The College of Pontifices was uppermost body in this hierarchy, and its chief priest, the *Pontifex Maximus*, was the head of the state religion.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Flamens took care of the cults of various gods, while augurs were trusted with taking the auspices.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The sacred king took on the religious responsibilities of the deposed kings.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman Empire, deceased emperors who had ruled well were deified by their successors and the Senate. and the formalised imperial cult became increasingly prominent.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] As contact with the Greeks increased, the old Roman gods became increasingly associated with Greek gods.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Under the Empire, the Romans absorbed the mythologies of their conquered subjects, often leading to situations in which the temples and priests of traditional Italian deities existed side by side with those of foreign gods.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning with Emperor Nero in the 1st century AD, Roman official policy towards Christianity was negative, and at some point, being a Christian could be punishable by death.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Under Emperor Diocletian, the persecution of Christians reached its peak.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] However, it became an officially supported religion in the Roman state under Diocletian's successor, Constantine I, with the signing of the Edict of Milan in 313, and quickly became dominant.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] All religions except Christianity were prohibited in 391 AD by an edict of Emperor Theodosius I.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Like many ancient cultures, concepts of ethics and morality, while sharing some commonalities with modern society, differed greatly in several important ways.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Because ancient civilisations like Rome were under constant threat of attack from marauding tribes, their culture was necessarily militaristic with martial skills being a prized attribute.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Whereas modern societies consider compassion a virtue, Roman society considered compassion a vice, a moral defect.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] One of the primary purposes of the gladiatorial games was to inoculate Roman citizens from this weakness.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Romans instead prized virtues such as courage and conviction (*virtus*), a sense of duty to one's people, moderation and avoiding excess (*moderatio*), forgiveness and understanding (*clementia*), fairness (*severitas*), and loyalty (*pietas*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society had well-established and restrictive norms related to sexuality, though as with many societies, the lion's share of the responsibilities fell on women.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Women were generally expected to be monogamous having only a single husband during their life (*univira*), though this was much less regarded by the elite, especially under the empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Women were expected to be modest in public avoiding any provocative appearance and to demonstrate absolute fidelity to their husbands (*pudicitia*).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Wearing a veil was a common expectation to preserve modesty.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Sex outside of marriage was generally frowned upon for men and women and was made illegal during the imperial period.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Nevertheless, prostitution was an accepted and regulated practice.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Public demonstrations of death, violence, and brutality were used as a source of entertainment in Roman communities; however it was also a way to maintain social order, demonstrate power, and signify communal unity.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman painting styles show Greek influences, and surviving examples are primarily frescoes used to adorn the walls and ceilings of country villas, though Roman literature includes mentions of paintings on wood, ivory, and other materials.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Several examples of Roman painting have been found at Pompeii, and from these art historians divide the history of Roman painting into four periods.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The first style of Roman painting was practised from the early 2nd century BC to the early- or mid-1st century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] It was mainly composed of imitations of marble and masonry, though sometimes including depictions of mythological characters.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The second style began during the early 1st century BC and attempted to depict realistically three-dimensional architectural features and landscapes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The third style occurred during the reign of Augustus (27 BC – 14 AD), and rejected the realism of the second style in favour of simple ornamentation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] A small architectural scene, landscape, or abstract design was placed in the center with a monochrome background.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The fourth style, which began in the 1st century AD, depicted scenes from mythology, while retaining architectural details and abstract patterns.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Portrait sculpture used youthful and classical proportions, evolving later into a mixture of realism and idealism.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During the Antonine and Severan periods, ornate hair and bearding, with deep cutting and drilling, became popular.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were also made in relief sculptures, usually depicting Roman victories.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman music was largely based on Greek music, and played an important part in many aspects of Roman life.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman military, musical instruments such as the *tuba* (a long trumpet) or the *cornu* were used to give various commands, while the *buccina* (possibly a trumpet or horn) and the *lituus* (probably an elongated J-shaped instrument), were used in ceremonial capacities.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Music was used in the Roman amphitheatres between fights and in the *odea*, and in these settings is known to have featured the *cornu* and the *hydraulis* (a type of water organ).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Most religious rituals featured musical performances.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Some music historians believe that music was used at almost all public ceremonies.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The graffiti, brothels, paintings, and sculptures found in Pompeii and Herculaneum suggest that the Romans had a sex-saturated culture.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Latin literature was, from its start, influenced heavily by Greek authors.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Some of the earliest extant works are of historical epics telling the early military history of Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] As the Republic expanded, authors began to produce poetry, comedy, history, and tragedy.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome's literary contributions are still recognised today and the works by ancient Roman authors were available in bookshops as well as in public and private libraries.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Many scholars and statesmen of ancient Rome cultivated private libraries that were used both as demonstrations of knowledge and displays of wealth and power.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Although Julius Caesar had intended to establish public libraries to further establish Rome as a great cultural center like Athens and Alexandria, he died before this was accomplished.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Caesar's former lieutenant, Gaius Asinius Pollio, took up the project and opened the first public library in Rome in the Atrium Libertatis.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Emperors Augustus, Tiberius, Vespasian, Domitian, and Trajan also founded or expanded public libraries in Rome during their reigns.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] These included the Ulpian Library in Trajan's Forum and libraries in the Temple of Apollo Palatinus, the Temple of Peace in the Roman Forum, the Temple of Divus Augustus, which was dedicated to Minerva when it was rebuilt under Emperor Domitian's orders.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] By the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the city of Rome had more than two dozen public libraries.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] As the Roman Empire spread, public libraries were established in other major cities and cultural centers including Ephesos, Athens, and Timgad.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Roman cuisine changed over the long duration of this ancient civilisation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Dietary habits were affected by the influence of Greek culture, the political changes from Kingdom to Republic to Empire, and the Empire's enormous expansion, which exposed Romans to many new, provincial culinary habits and cooking techniques.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the beginning the differences between social classes were relatively small, but disparities evolved with the Empire's growth.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Men and women drank wine with their meals.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman diet included many items that are staples of modern Italian cooking.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] However, some foods now considered characteristic of modern Italian cuisine were not used.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In particular, spinach and eggplant (aubergine) were introduced later from the Arab world, and tomatoes, potatoes, capsicum peppers, and maize (the modern source of polenta) only appeared in Europe following the discovery of the New World and the Columbian Exchange.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans knew of rice, but it was very rarely available to them.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Butcher's meat such as beef was an uncommon luxury.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The most popular meat was pork, especially sausages.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Fish was more common than meat, with a sophisticated aquaculture and large-scale industries devoted to oyster farming.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also engaged in snail farming and oak grub farming.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Some fish were greatly esteemed and fetched high prices, such as mullet raised in the fishery at Cosa, and "elaborate means were invented to assure its freshness".
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, a breakfast called *ientaculum* was served at dawn.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] At mid-day to early afternoon, Romans ate *cena*, the main meal of the day, and at nightfall a light supper called *vesperna*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] With the increased importation of foreign foods, the *cena* grew larger in size and included a wider range of foods.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, it gradually shifted to the evening, while the *vesperna* was abandoned completely over the course of the years.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The mid-day meal *prandium* became a light meal to hold one over until *cena*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The toga, a common garment during the era of Julius Caesar, was gradually abandoned by all social classes of the Empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] At the early 4th century, the toga had become just a garment worn by senators in Senate and ceremonial events.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] At the 4th century, the toga was replaced by the *paenula* (a garment similar to a poncho) as the everyday garment of the Romans, from the lower classes to the upper classes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Another garment that was popular among the Romans in the later years of the Western Roman Empire was the *pallium*, which was mostly worn by philosophers and scholars in general.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Due to external influences, mainly from the Germanic peoples, the Romans adopted tunics very similar to those used by the Germanic peoples with whom they interacted in the final years of the Western Empire, also adopted trousers and hats like the *pileus pannonicus*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] During the Late Empire, the *paludamentum* (a type of military clothing) was used only by the Emperor of Rome (since the reign of Augustus, the first emperor) while the dalmatic (also used by the Christian clergy) began to spread throughout the empire.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The youth of Rome had several forms of athletic play and exercise.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Play for boys was supposed to prepare them for active military service, such as jumping, wrestling, boxing, and racing.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the countryside, pastimes for the wealthy also included fishing and hunting.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also had several forms of ball playing, including one resembling handball.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Dice games, board games, and gamble games were popular pastimes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] For the wealthy, dinner parties presented an opportunity for entertainment, sometimes featuring music, dancing, and poetry readings.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The majority, less well-off, sometimes enjoyed similar parties through clubs or associations, but for most Romans, recreational dining usually meant patronising taverns.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Children entertained themselves with toys and such games as leapfrog.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Public games and spectacles were sponsored by leading Romans who wished to advertise their generosity and court popular approval; in Rome or its provinces, this usually meant the emperor or his governors.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Venues in Rome and the provinces were developed specifically for public games.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Rome's Colosseum was built in 70 AD under the Roman emperor Vespasian and opened in 80 AD to host other events and gladiatorial combats.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Gladiators sometimes fought to the death, but more often to an adjudicated victory, usually in keeping with the mood of the watching crowd.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Shows of exotic animals were popular in their own right; but sometimes animals were pitted against human beings, either armed professionals or unarmed criminals who had been condemned to public death.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Chariot racing was extremely popular among all classes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, these races were usually held at the Circus Maximus, which had been purpose-built for chariot and horse-racing and, as Rome's largest public place, was also used for festivals and animal shows.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome boasted impressive technological feats, using many advancements that were lost in the Middle Ages and not rivalled again until the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] An example of this is insulated glazing, which was not invented again until the 1930s.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Many practical Roman innovations were adopted from earlier Greek designs.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were often divided and based on craft.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Artisans guarded technologies as trade secrets.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Roman civil engineering and military engineering constituted a large part of Rome's technological superiority and legacy, and contributed to the construction of hundreds of roads, bridges, aqueducts, public baths, theatres and arenas.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Many monuments, such as the Colosseum, Pont du Gard, and Pantheon, remain as testaments to Roman engineering and culture.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans were renowned for their architecture, which is grouped with Greek traditions into "Classical architecture".
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Although there were many differences from Greek architecture, Rome borrowed heavily from Greece in adhering to strict, formulaic building designs and proportions.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Aside from two new orders of columns, composite and Tuscan, and from the dome, which was derived from the Etruscan arch, Rome had relatively few architectural innovations until the end of the Republic.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] In the 1st century BC, Romans started to use Roman concrete widely.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Concrete was invented in the late 3rd century BC.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] It was a powerful cement derived from pozzolana, and soon supplanted marble as the chief Roman building material and allowed many daring architectural forms.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Also in the 1st century BC, Vitruvius wrote *De architectura*, possibly the first complete treatise on architecture in history.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also largely built using timber, causing a rapid decline of the woodlands surrounding Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] It is suggested that timber, around 4 metres (13 ft) long, came up to Rome via the Tiber River on ships travelling across the Mediterranean Sea from the confluence of the Saône and Rhône rivers in what is now the city of Lyon in present-day France.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] With solid foundations and good drainage, Roman roads were known for their durability and many segments of the Roman road system were still in use a thousand years after the fall of Rome.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The construction of a vast and efficient travel network throughout the Empire dramatically increased Rome's power and influence.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] They allowed Roman legions to be deployed rapidly, with predictable marching times between key points of the empire, no matter the season.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] These highways also had enormous economic significance, solidifying Rome's role as a trading crossroads—the origin of the saying "all roads lead to Rome".
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman government maintained a system of way stations, known as the *cursus publicus*, and established a system of horse relays allowing a dispatch to travel up to 80 km (50 mi) a day.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans constructed numerous aqueducts to supply water to cities and industrial sites and to aid in their agriculture.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] By the third century, the city of Rome was supplied by 11 aqueducts with a combined length of 450 km (280 mi).
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also made major advancements in sanitation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Romans were particularly famous for their public baths, called *thermae*, which were used for both hygienic and social purposes.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Many Roman houses had flush toilets and indoor plumbing, and a complex sewer system, the *Cloaca Maxima*, was used to drain the local marshes and carry waste into the Tiber.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have speculated that lead pipes in the sewer and plumbing systems led to widespread lead poisoning, which contributed to fall of Rome; however, lead content would have been minimised.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] Ancient Rome is the progenitor of Western civilisation.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] The customs, religion, law, technology, architecture, political system, military, literature, languages, alphabet, government and many factors and aspects of western civilisation are all inherited from Roman advancements.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] The rediscovery of Roman culture revitalised Western civilisation, playing a role in the Renaissance and the Age of Enlightenment.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] The two longest ancient accounts of the Roman history, the histories of Livy and Dionysius of Halicarnassus, were composed 500 years later than the date for the founding of the republic and 200 years from the defeat of Hannibal.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] Although there has been a diversity of works on ancient Roman history, many of them are lost.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] As a result of this loss, there are gaps in Roman history, which are filled by unreliable works, such as the **Historia Augusta**.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] Caesar wrote his own accounts of his military campaigns in Gaul and during the Civil War in part to impress his contemporaries.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] In the Empire, the biographies of famous men and early emperors flourished, examples being *The Twelve Caesars* of Suetonius, and Plutarch's *Parallel Lives*.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] Other major works of Imperial times were that of Livy and Tacitus.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] Interest in studying, and idealising, ancient Rome became prevalent during the Italian Renaissance.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] Edward Gibbon's *The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* "began the modern study of Roman history in the English-speaking world".
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] Barthold Georg Niebuhr was a founder of the examination of ancient Roman history and wrote *The Roman History*, tracing the period until the First Punic War.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] During the Napoleonic, *The History of Romans* by Victor Duruy highlighted the Caesarean period popular at the time.
[src:keel-laying/ancient-rome-p03] *History of Rome*, *Roman constitutional law* and *Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum*, all by Theodor Mommsen, became milestones.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Ship launching imposes stresses on the ship not met during normal operation and in addition to the size and weight of the vessel represents a considerable engineering challenge as well as a public spectacle.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The process also involves many traditions intended to invite good luck, such as christening by breaking a sacrificial bottle of champagne over the bow as the ship is named aloud and launched.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] There are three principal methods of conveying a new ship from building site to water, only two of which are called "launching".
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The oldest, most familiar, and most widely used is the end-on launch, in which the vessel slides down an inclined slipway, usually stern first.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] With the side launch, the ship enters the water broadside.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] This method came into use in the 19th century on inland waters, rivers, and lakes, and was more widely adopted during World War II.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The third method is float-out, used for ships that are built in basins or dry docks and then floated by admitting water into the dock.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] If launched in a restrictive waterway, drag chains are used to slow the ship speed to prevent it striking the opposite bank.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Normally, ways are arranged perpendicular to the shore line (or as nearly so as the water and maximum length of vessel allows) and the ship is built with its stern facing the water.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Where the launch takes place into a narrow river, the building slips may be at a shallow angle rather than perpendicular, even though this requires a longer slipway when launching.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Modern slipways take the form of a reinforced concrete mat of sufficient strength to support the vessel, with two "barricades" that extend well below the water level taking into account tidal variations.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The barricades support the two launch ways.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The vessel is built upon temporary cribbing that is arranged to give access to the hull's outer bottom and to allow the launchways to be erected under the complete hull.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] When it is time to prepare for launching, a pair of standing ways is erected under the hull and out onto the barricades.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] (Tallow and whale oil were used as grease in sailing ship days.) A pair of sliding ways is placed on top, under the hull, and a launch cradle with bow and stern poppets is erected on these sliding ways.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The weight of the hull is then transferred from the build cribbing onto the launch cradle.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Provision is made to hold the vessel in place and then release it at the appropriate moment in the launching ceremony; common mechanisms include weak links designed to be cut at a signal and mechanical triggers controlled by a switch from the ceremonial platform.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] On launching, the vessel slides backwards down the slipway on the ways until it floats by itself.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Some slipways are built so that the vessel is side-on to the water and is launched sideways.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] This is done where the limitations of the water channel would not allow lengthwise launching, but occupies a much greater length of shore.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] *The Great Eastern* designed by Brunel was built this way, as were many landing craft during World War II.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] This method requires many more sets of ways to support the weight of the ship.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Sometimes ships are launched using a series of inflated tubes underneath the hull, which deflate to cause a downward slope into the water.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] This procedure has the advantages of requiring less permanent infrastructure, risk, and cost.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The airbags provide support to the hull of the ship and aid its launching motion into the water, thus this method is arguably safer than other options such as sideways launching.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] These airbags are usually cylindrical in shape with hemispherical heads at both ends.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] It is believed that ancient Egyptians, Greeks, and Romans called on their gods to protect seamen.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Favor was evoked from the monarch of the seas—Poseidon in Greek mythology, Neptune in Roman mythology.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Ship launching participants in ancient Greece wreathed their heads with olive branches, drank wine to honor the gods, and poured water on the new vessel as a symbol of blessing.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Shrines were carried on board Greek and Roman ships, and this practice extended into the Middle Ages.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The shrine was usually placed at the quarterdeck, an area which continues to have special ceremonial significance.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Different peoples and cultures shaped the religious ceremonies surrounding a ship launching.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Jews and Christians customarily used wine and water as they called upon God to safeguard them at sea.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Intercession of the saints and the blessing of the church were asked by Christians.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Ship launchings in the Ottoman Empire were accompanied by prayers to Allah, the sacrifice of sheep, and appropriate feasting.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The liturgical aspects of ship christenings, or baptisms, continued in Catholic countries, while the Reformation seems to have put a stop to them for a time in Protestant Europe.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] By the 17th century, for example, English launchings were secular affairs.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The christening party for the launch of the 64-gun ship of the line *Prince Royal* in 1610 included the Prince of Wales and famed naval constructor Phineas Pett, who was master shipwright at the Woolwich yard.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The "standing cup" was a large cup fashioned of precious metal.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] When the ship began to slide down the ways, the presiding official took a ceremonial sip of wine from the cup, and poured the rest on the deck or over the bow.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Usually the cup was thrown overboard and belonged to the lucky retriever.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] As navies grew larger and launchings more frequent, economy dictated that the costly cup be caught in a net for reuse at other launchings.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Late in 17th century Britain, the standing-cup ceremony was replaced by the practice of breaking a bottle across the bow.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Launching could be said to mark the birth of a vessel; and people throughout history have performed launching ceremonies, in part to appeal for good fortune and the safety of each new vessel.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] In Canada, Aboriginal peoples will perform ceremonies at the launching of vessels along with other methods of launching.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] French ship launchings and christenings in the 18th and early 19th centuries were accompanied by unique rites closely resembling marriage and baptismal ceremonies.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] A godfather for the new ship presented a godmother with a bouquet of flowers as both said the ship's name.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] No bottle was broken, but a priest pronounced the vessel's name and blessed it with holy water.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] In India, ships have historically been launched with a Puja ceremony that dedicates the ship to a Hindu god or goddess, and seeks blessings for her and her sailors.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Historically, Hindu priests would perform the *puja* ceremony at launch.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] In the 20th century, ships were launched with a lady breaking a coconut on the bow of the vessel, which is sometimes followed by a small Puja.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Japanese ship launchings incorporate silver axes which are thought to bring good luck and scare away evil.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Japanese shipbuilders traditionally order the crafting of a special axe for each new vessel; and after the launching ceremony, they present the axe to the vessel's owner as a commemorative gift.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The axe is used to cut the rope which tethers the ship to the place where she was built.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Sponsors of British warships were customarily members of the royal family, senior naval officers, or Admiralty officials.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] A few civilians were invited to sponsor Royal Navy ships during the nineteenth century, and women became sponsors for the first time.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] In 1875, a religious element was returned to naval christenings by Princess Alexandra, wife of the Prince of Wales, when she introduced an Anglican choral service in the launching ceremony for battleship *Alexandra*.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] In 1969, Queen Elizabeth II named the ocean liner *Queen Elizabeth 2* after herself, instead of the older liner RMS *Queen Elizabeth*, by saying, "I name this ship *Queen Elizabeth the Second*.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The Duchess of Rothesay similarly launched HMS *Prince of Wales* by pulling a lever which smashed a bottle of single malt Scotch whisky at the side of the ship.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] At the 2024 launching of CalMac ferry *Glen Rosa*, newly-qualified welder Beth Atkinson named the ship and pulled a lever to similarly smash a bottle, of single malt from the Ardgowan distillery at nearby Inverkip.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Shipyard ephemera is a rich source of detail concerning a launch and this was often material produced for the audience of the day and then thrown away.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Tyne & Wear Archives & Museums has many of these items from Tyne and Wear shipyards.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The 1900 piece for *Eidsvold* reproduced in this article lists a woman performing the launch.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Ceremonial practices for christening and launching ships in the United States have their roots in Europe.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] It was customary for the builders to celebrate a ship launching.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Rhode Island authorities were charged with overseeing construction of frigates *Warren* and *Providence*.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] No mention has come to light of christening a Continental Navy ship during the American Revolution.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The first ships of the Continental Navy were *Alfred*, *Cabot*, *Andrew Doria*, and *Columbus*.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] These were former merchantmen, and their names were assigned during conversion and outfitting.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Later, Congress authorized the construction of thirteen frigates, and no names were assigned until after four had launched.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The first description that we have of an American warship christening is that of *Constitution* at Boston, October 21, 1797, famous as "Old Ironsides." Her sponsor was Captain James Sever, USN, who stood on the weather deck at the bow.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] "At fifteen minutes after twelve she commenced a movement into the water with such steadiness, majesty and exactness as to fill every heart with sensations of joy and delight." As *Constitution* ran out, Captain Sever broke a bottle of fine old Madeira over the heel of the bowsprit.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] As the 19th century progressed, American ship launchings continued to be festive occasions, but with no set ritual except that the sponsor(s) used some "christening fluid" as the ship received her name.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Sloop of war *Concord* was launched in 1828 and was "christened by a young lady of Portsmouth." This is the first known instance of a woman sponsoring a United States Navy vessel.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The contemporaneous account does not name her.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The first *identified* woman sponsor was Lavinia Fanning Watson, daughter of a prominent Philadelphian.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] She broke a bottle of wine and water over the bow of sloop-of-war *Germantown* at Philadelphia Navy Yard on August 22, 1846.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Women as sponsors became increasingly the rule, but not universally so.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] As sloop-of-war *Plymouth* "glided along the inclined plane" in 1846, "two young sailors, one stationed at each side of her head, anointed her with bottles, and named her as she left her cradle for the deep." As late as 1898, the torpedo boat *MacKenzie* was christened by the son of the builder.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Wine is the traditional christening fluid, although numerous other liquids have been used.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] *Princeton* and *Raritan* were sent on their way in 1843 with whisky.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Seven years later, "a bottle of best brandy was broken over the bow of steam sloop *San Jacinto*." Steam frigate *Merrimack* earned her place in naval history as Confederate States of America ironclad *Virginia*, and she was baptized with water from the Merrimack River.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Admiral David Farragut's famous American Civil War flagship steam sloop *Hartford* was christened by three sponsors; two young ladies broke bottles of Connecticut River water and Hartford, Connecticut spring water, while a naval lieutenant completed the ceremony with a bottle of sea water.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Champagne came into popular use as a christening fluid as the 19th century closed.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] A granddaughter of Secretary of the Navy Benjamin F.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Tracy wet the bow of *Maine*, the Navy's first steel battleship, with champagne at the New York Navy Yard on November 18, 1890.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The effects of national prohibition on alcoholic beverages were reflected to some extent in ship christenings.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Cruisers *Pensacola* and *Houston*, for example, were christened with water; the submarine *V-6* with cider.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] However, battleship *California* appropriately received her name with California wine in 1919.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Champagne returned in 1922, but only for the launch of light cruiser *Trenton*.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Rigid naval airships *Los Angeles*, *Shenandoah*, *Akron*, and *Macon* were built during the 1920s and early 1930s, carried on the Naval Vessel Register, and each was formally commissioned.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The earliest First Lady of the United States to act as sponsor was Grace Coolidge who christened the airship *Los Angeles*.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Lou Henry Hoover christened *Akron* in 1931, but the customary bottle was not used.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Instead, the First Lady pulled a cord which opened a hatch in the airship's towering nose to release a flock of pigeons.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] Thousands of ships of every description came off the ways during World War II, the concerted effort of a mobilized American industry.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] The historic christening and launching ceremonies continued, but travel restrictions, other wartime considerations, and sheer numbers dictated that such occasions be less elaborate than those in the years before the war.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] On 15 December 1941, the United States Maritime Commission announced that as a war-time measure all formal launching ceremonies would be discontinued for merchant ships being constructed under its authority, though simple informal ceremonies could continue without reimbursement to builders.
[src:keel-laying/ceremonial-ship-launching] In addition to the ceremonial breaking of a champagne bottle on the bow, the sponsor remains in contact with the ship's crew and is involved in special events such as homecomings.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The custom is primarily associated with the ancient Greeks and Romans, though it is also found in the ancient Near East.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Western Europe, a similar usage of coins in burials occurs in regions inhabited by Celts of the Gallo-Roman, Hispano-Roman and Romano-British cultures, and among the Germanic peoples of late antiquity and the early Christian era, with sporadic examples into the early 20th century.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Although archaeology shows that the myth reflects an actual custom, the placement of coins with the dead was neither pervasive nor confined to a single coin in the deceased's mouth.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In many burials, inscribed metal-leaf tablets or exonumia take the place of the coin, or gold-foil crosses during the early Christian period.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The presence of coins or a coin-hoard in Germanic ship-burials suggests an analogous concept.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The phrase "Charon's obol" as used by archaeologists sometimes can be understood as referring to a particular religious rite, but often serves as a kind of shorthand for coinage as grave goods presumed to further the deceased's passage into the afterlife.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Latin, Charon's obol sometimes is called a *viaticum*, or "sustenance for the journey"; the placement of the coin on the mouth has been explained also as a seal to protect the deceased's soul or to prevent it from returning.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] All of these pseudo-coins have no sign of attachment, are too thin for normal use, and are often found in burial sites.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The coin for Charon is conventionally referred to in Greek literature as an *obolós* (ὀβολός), one of the basic denominations of ancient Greek coinage, worth one-sixth of a drachma.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Among the Greeks, coins in actual burials are sometimes also a *danakē* (δανάκη) or other relatively small-denomination gold, silver, bronze or copper coin in local use.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Roman literary sources the coin is usually bronze or copper.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Latin, Charon's obol is sometimes called a *viaticum*, which in everyday usage means "provision for a journey" (from *via*, 'way, road, journey'), encompassing food, money and other supplies.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The same word can refer to the living allowance granted to those stripped of their property and condemned to exile, and by metaphorical extension to preparing for death at the end of life's journey.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Drawing on this metaphorical sense of "provision for the journey into death," ecclesiastical Latin borrowed the term *viaticum* for the form of Eucharist that is placed in the mouth of a person who is dying as provision for the soul's passage to eternal life.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The earliest literary evidence of this Christian usage for *viaticum* appears in Paulinus's account of the death of Saint Ambrose in 397 AD.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] And because of this it is called the *viaticum*, since it provides us with the way of getting there"; the idea of Christians as "travelers in search of salvation" finds early expression in the *Confessions* of St.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Greek epigrams that were literary versions of epitaphs refer to "the obol that pays the passage of the departed," with some epigrams referring to the belief by mocking or debunking it.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The incongruity of paying what is, in effect, admission to Hell encouraged a comic or satiric treatment, and Charon as a ferryman who must be persuaded, threatened, or bribed to do his job appears to be a literary construct that is not reflected in early classical art.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Christiane Sourvinou-Inwood has shown that in 5th-century BC depictions of Charon, as on the funerary vases called lekythoi, he is a non-threatening, even reassuring presence who guides women, adolescents, and children to the afterlife.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The use of coins as grave goods shows a variety of practice that casts doubt on the accuracy of the term "Charon's obol" as an interpretational category.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The phrase continues to be used, however, to suggest the ritual or religious significance of coinage in a funerary context.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The jawbones of skulls found in certain burials in Roman Britain are stained greenish from contact with a copper coin; Roman coins are found later in Anglo-Saxon graves, but often pierced for wearing as a necklace or amulet.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Among the ancient Greeks, only about 5 to 10 percent of known burials contain any coins at all; in some Roman cremation cemeteries, however, as many as half the graves yield coins.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Many if not most of these occurrences conform to the myth of Charon's obol in neither the number of coins nor their positioning.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Variety of placement and number, including but not limited to a single coin in the mouth, is characteristic of all periods and places.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Some of the oldest coins from Mediterranean tombs have been found on Cyprus.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In 2001 Destrooper-Georgiades, a specialist in Achaemenid numismatics, said that investigations of 33 tombs had yielded 77 coins.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Although denomination varies, as does the number in any given burial, small coins predominate.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Coins started to be placed in tombs almost as soon as they came into circulation on the island in the 6th century BC, and some predate both the first issue of the obol and any literary reference to Charon's fee.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Although only a small percentage of Greek burials contain coins, among these there are widespread examples of a single coin positioned in the mouth of a skull or with cremation remains.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In cremation urns, the coin sometimes adheres to the jawbone of the skull.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] At Olynthus, 136 coins (mostly bronze, but some silver), were found with burials; in 1932, archaeologists reported that 20 graves had each contained four bronze coins, which they believed were intended for placement in the mouth.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A few tombs at Olynthus have contained two coins, but more often a single bronze coin was positioned in the mouth or within the head of the skeleton.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Hellenistic-era tombs at one cemetery in Athens, coins, usually bronze, were found most often in the dead person's mouth, though sometimes in the hand, loose in the grave, or in a vessel.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In excavations of 91 tombs at a cemetery in Amphipolis during the mid- to late 1990s, a majority of the dead were found to have a coin in the mouth.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The burials dated from the 4th to the late 2nd century BC.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A notable use of a danake occurred in the burial of a woman in 4th-century BC Thessaly, a likely initiate into the Orphic or Dionysiac mysteries.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Her religious paraphernalia included gold tablets inscribed with instructions for the afterlife and a terracotta figure of a Bacchic worshipper.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Upon her lips was placed a gold danake stamped with the Gorgon's head.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Coins begin to appear with greater frequency in graves during the 3rd century BC, along with gold wreaths and plain unguentaria (small bottles for oil) in place of the earlier lekythoi.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Black-figure lekythoi had often depicted Dionysiac scenes; the later white-ground vessels often show Charon, usually with his pole, but rarely (or dubiously) accepting the coin.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The Black Sea region has also produced examples of Charon's obol.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] At Apollonia Pontica, the custom had been practiced from the mid-4th century BC; in one cemetery, for instance, 17 percent of graves contained small bronze local coins in the mouth or hand of the deceased.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] During 1998 excavations of Pichvnari, on the coast of present-day Georgia, a single coin was found in seven burials, and a pair of coins in two.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The coins, silver triobols of the local Colchian currency, were located near the mouth, with the exception of one that was near the hand.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] It is unclear whether the dead were Colchians or Greeks.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The investigating archaeologists did not regard the practice as typical of the region, but speculate that the local geography lent itself to adapting the Greek myth, as bodies of the dead in actuality had to be ferried across a river from the town to the cemetery.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Charon's obol is usually regarded as Hellenic, and a single coin in burials is often taken as a mark of Hellenization, but the practice may be independent of Greek influence in some regions.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The placing of a coin in the mouth of the deceased is found also during Parthian and Sasanian times in what is now Iran.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Curiously, the coin was not the danake of Persian origin, as it was sometimes among the Greeks, but usually a Greek drachma.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In the Yazdi region, objects consecrated in graves may include a coin or piece of silver; the custom is thought to be perhaps as old as the Seleucid era and may be a form of Charon's obol.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Some burials from the Ard-al-Moharbeen necropolis, a Roman cemetery in the Gaza Strip, were discovered with coins in their mouths.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Discoveries of a single coin near the skull in tombs of the Levant suggest a similar practice among Phoenicians in the Persian period.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Jewish ossuaries sometimes contain a single coin; for example, in an ossuary bearing the inscriptional name "Miriam, daughter of Simeon," a coin minted during the reign of Herod Agrippa I, dated 42/43 AD, was found in the skull's mouth.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Cemeteries in the Western Roman Empire vary widely: in a 1st-century BC community in Cisalpine Gaul, coins were included in more than 40 percent of graves, but none was placed in the mouth of the deceased; the figure is only 10 percent for cremations at Empúries in Spain and York in Britain.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] On the Iberian Peninsula, evidence interpreted as Charon's obol has been found at Tarragona.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Belgic Gaul, varying deposits of coins are found with the dead for the 1st through 3rd centuries, but are most frequent in the late 4th and early 5th centuries.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Thirty Gallo-Roman burials near the Pont de Pasly, Soissons, each contained a coin for Charon.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Germanic burials show a preference for gold coins, but even within a single cemetery and a narrow time period, their disposition varies.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In one Merovingian cemetery of Frénouville, Normandy, which was in use for four centuries after Christ, coins are found in a minority of the graves.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] At one time, the cemetery was regarded as exhibiting two distinct phases: an earlier Gallo-Roman period when the dead were buried with vessels, notably of glass, and Charon's obol; and later, when they were given funerary dress and goods according to Frankish custom.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] This neat division, however, has been shown to be misleading.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In the 3rd- to 4th-century area of the cemetery, coins were placed near the skulls or hands, sometimes protected by a pouch or vessel, or were found in the grave-fill as if tossed in.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Bronze coins usually numbered one or two per grave, as would be expected from the custom of Charon's obol, but one burial contained 23 bronze coins, and another held a gold solidus and a *semissis*.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The latter examples indicate that coins might have represented relative social status.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In the newer part of the cemetery, which remained in use through the 6th century, the deposition patterns for coinage were similar, but the coins themselves were not contemporaneous with the burials, and some were pierced for wearing.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The use of older coins may reflect a shortage of new currency, or may indicate that the old coins held a traditional symbolic meaning apart from their denominational value.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] "The varied placement of coins of different values ... demonstrates at least partial if not complete loss of understanding of the original religious function of Charon’s obol," remarks Bonnie Effros, a specialist in Merovingian burial customs.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Although the rite of Charon's obol was practiced no more uniformly in Northern Europe than in Greece, there are examples of individual burials or small groups conforming to the pattern.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] At Broadstairs in Kent, a young man had been buried with a Merovingian gold tremissis (*ca.* 575) in his mouth.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A gold-plated coin was found in the mouth of a young man buried on the Isle of Wight in the mid-6th century; his other grave goods included vessels, a drinking horn, a knife, and gaming-counters of ivory with one cobalt-blue glass piece.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Scandinavian and Germanic gold bracteates found in burials of the 5th and 6th centuries, particularly those in Britain, have also been interpreted in light of Charon's obol.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] These gold disks, similar to coins though generally single-sided, were influenced by late Roman imperial coins and medallions but feature iconography from Norse myth and runic inscriptions.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The stamping process created an extended rim that forms a frame with a loop for threading; the bracteates often appear in burials as a woman's necklace.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A function comparable to that of Charon's obol is suggested by examples such as a man's burial at Monkton in Kent and a group of several male graves on Gotland, Sweden, for which the bracteate was deposited in a pouch beside the body.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In the Gotland burials, the bracteates lack rim and loop, and show no traces of wear, suggesting that they had not been intended for everyday use.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] It has been conjectured that the coins were to pay the oarsmen who would row the ship into the next world, while the ingots were meant for the steersmen.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Although Charon is usually a lone figure in depictions from both antiquity and the modern era, there is some slight evidence that his ship might be furnished with oarsmen.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A fragment of 6th century BC pottery has been interpreted as Charon sitting in the stern as steersman of a boat fitted with ten pairs of oars and rowed by *eidola* (εἴδωλα), shades of the dead.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A reference in Lucian seems also to imply that the shades might row the boat.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Scandinavia, scattered examples of Charon's obol have been documented from the Roman Iron Age and the Migration Period; in the Viking Age eastern Sweden produces the best evidence, Denmark rarely, and Norway and Finland inconclusively.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In the 13th and 14th centuries, Charon's obol appears in graves in Sweden, Scania, and Norway.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Swedish folklore documents the custom from the 18th into the 20th century.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The custom of Charon's obol not only continued into the Christian era, but was adopted by Christians, as a single coin was sometimes placed in the mouth for Christian burials.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] At Arcy-Sainte-Restitue in Picardy, a Merovingian grave yielded a coin of Constantine I, the first Christian emperor, used as Charon's obol.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Britain, the practice was just as frequent, if not more so, among Christians and persisted even to the end of the 19th century.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A folklorist writing in 1914 was able to document a witness in Britain who had seen a penny placed in the mouth of an old man as he lay in his coffin.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In 1878, Pope Pius IX was entombed with a coin.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The practice was widely documented around the turn of the 19th and 20th centuries in Greece, where the coin was sometimes accompanied by a key.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] So-called "ghost coins" also appear with the dead.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] These are impressions of an actual coin or numismatic icon struck into a small piece of gold foil.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In a 5th- or 4th-century BC grave at Syracuse, Sicily, a small rectangular gold leaf stamped with a dual-faced figure, possibly Demeter/Kore, was found in the skeleton's mouth.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In a marble cremation box from the mid-2nd century BC, the "Charon's piece" took the form of a bit of gold foil stamped with an owl; in addition to the charred bone fragments, the box also contained gold leaves from a wreath of the type sometimes associated with the mystery religions.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Within an Athenian family burial plot of the 2nd century BC, a thin gold disk similarly stamped with the owl of Athens had been placed in the mouth of each male.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Several of these prayer sheets have been found in positions that indicate placement in or on the deceased's mouth.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A functional equivalence with the Charon's piece is further suggested by the evidence of flattened coins used as mouth coverings (*epistomia*) from graves in Crete.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] A gold phylactery with a damaged inscription invoking the syncretic god Sarapis was found within the skull in a burial from the late 1st century AD in southern Rome.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The gold tablet may have served both as a protective amulet during the deceased's lifetime and then, with its insertion into the mouth, possibly on the model of Charon's obol, as a *Totenpass*.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In a late Roman-era burial in Douris, near Baalbek, Lebanon, the forehead, nose, and mouth of the deceased — a woman, in so far as skeletal remains can indicate — were covered with sheets of gold-leaf.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] She wore a wreath made from gold oak leaves, and her clothing had been sewn with gold-leaf ovals decorated with female faces.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Several glass vessels were arranged at her feet, and her discoverers interpreted the bronze coin close to her head as an example of Charon's obol.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Textual evidence also exists for covering portions of the deceased's body with gold foil.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The early Christian poet Prudentius seems to be referring either to these inscribed gold-leaf tablets or to the larger gold-foil coverings in one of his condemnations of the mystery religions.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Prudentius says that *auri lammina* ("sheets of gold") were placed on the bodies of initiates as part of funeral rites.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In Gaul and in Alemannic territory, Christian graves of the Merovingian period reveal an analogous Christianized practice in the form of gold or gold-alloy leaf shaped like a cross, imprinted with designs, and deposited possibly as votives or amulets for the deceased.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] These paper-thin, fragile gold crosses are sometimes referred to by scholars with the German term *Goldblattkreuze*.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] They appear to have been sewn onto the deceased's garment just before burial, not worn during life, and in this practice are comparable to the pierced Roman coins found in Anglo-Saxon graves that were attached to clothing instead of or in addition to being threaded onto a necklace.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The crosses are characteristic of Lombardic Italy (Cisalpine Gaul of the Roman imperial era), where they were fastened to veils and placed over the deceased's mouth in a continuation of Byzantine practice.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Throughout the Lombardic realm and north into Germanic territory, the crosses gradually replaced bracteates during the 7th century.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The transition is signalled by Scandinavian bracteates found in Kent that are stamped with cross motifs resembling the Lombardic crosses.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Two plain gold-foil crosses of Latin form, found in the burial of a 7th-century East Saxon king, are the first known examples from England, announced in 2004.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] The king's other grave goods included glass vessels made in England and two different Merovingian gold coins, each of which had a cross on the reverse.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Coins of the period were adapted with Christian iconography in part to facilitate their use as an alternative to amulets of traditional religions.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Scandinavia also produced small and fragile gold-foil pieces, called *gullgubber*, that were worked in repoussé with human figures.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] These begin to appear in the late Iron Age and continue into the Viking Age.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] In form they resemble the gold-foil pieces such as those found at Douris, but the *gullgubber* were not fashioned with a fastening element and are not associated with burials.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] They occur in the archaeological record sometimes singly, but most often in large numbers.
[src:keel-laying/charon-s-obol-p01] Ships often appear in Greek and Roman funerary art representing a voyage to the Isles of the Blessed, and a 2nd-century sarcophagus found in Velletri, near Rome, included Charon's boat among its subject matter.
